Homemade gnocchi with a gochujang cream sauce 

_____
HOMADEMADE GNOCCHI WITH GOCHUJANG CREAM SAUCE
1 potato, peeled
1 cup 00 Flour (equal parts to riced potato)
Salt and pepper to taste
1 medium egg
1/4 cup ricotta cheese
1 tbsp unsalted butter
1 small shallots
1 tbsp gochujang
1/4 cup heavy cream

METHOD
In medium pot, bring water to a boil and salt generously. Cut potato into quarters and add to water. Boil until fork tender.

Run cooked potato through a ricer onto a clean surface. Create a small well in the center and add egg. Add ricotta to the edges of the well and season with salt and pepper. Add flour over the potatoes and use a pastry scraper to combine. Then, gently knead the dough into a log - the dough should not stick to your fingers, if it does, simply add more flour. Cut the log into eighth, then roll out each piece into a long rope. Cut the rope into 1 inch pieces. Then, using the back of a fork, gently roll each piece to create ridges. Add more flour over the gnocchi and let rest for about 15-20 minutes.

Heat a sauce pan on medium-high, then add butter and shallots. Cook until fragrant, about 1 minute, then add gochujang and heavy cream. Toss in gnocchi. Serve with parmesan cheese and parsley.

matcha perfection • super easy holiday treat for those on the nice list this year ♥️ 

_____

WHITE CHOCOLATE MATCHA COOKIES

Ingredients
1 tablespoon matcha power
150g all-purpose flour
A pinch of salt
2g (1/2 tsp) baking soda
15g (2 tbsp) corn starch
130g granulated sugar
100g brown sugar
2 teaspoon vanilla extract
114g (1 stick) melted butter
1 large Egg
12.5g White chocolate, chopped

Method
Preheat oven to 350. 

In medium bowl, combine flour, baking soda, corn starch,  matcha and a pinch of salt and set aside. 

In a large bowl, combine granulated sugar, brown sugar, vanilla, egg and melted butter. 

Slowly combine mixture to the wet mixture until it forms a dough. Fold in white chocolate. 

Refrigerate for 30 minute.

Scoop dough onto cookie sheet and bake for 10 minutes. Remove from oven and let rest for another 10 minutes.

time for a holiday treat with @oishii.berry 🍓 • pavlova wreath topped with fresh strawberries, gooseberries, pistachio and mint - the perfect holiday centerpiece
_____

PAVOLOVA WREATH
Ingredients
5 oz (4-5) egg whites
1 cup caster sugar
1 tbsp corn starch
1 tsp white vinegar
1 tsp vanilla extract

Toppings
1 cup Dairy-free whipped cream
1 box Oishii Strawberries
Gooseberries
Mint leaves
Pistachio
Powdered Sugar

METHOD
Separate egg whites from yolks, and let the whites come to room temperature.*

Preheat oven to 250.

In a large mixing bowl, beat egg whites on high until soft peaks form.

Slowly add in sugar (preferable 1/2 tbsp at a time to ensure the sugar fully dissolves). Continue to beat egg and sugar until the mixture has no grit.  The mixture should be glossy and form stiff peaks.

Fold in corn starch and vinegar until well combined.

Line the back of a sheet pan with parchment paper and place a ramekin at the center. 

Using a spatula, place the fluff around the ramekin to create a ring. The fluff should stand approximately 2” high.

Remove the center ramekin.  Place wreath in the oven and turn the oven down to 200.  Bake for 2 hours.**

Turn the oven off and let it cool in the oven. 

Just before serving, top the pavlova with whipped cream, strawberries and other fruit toppings. 

*Tips: it’s easier to separate the yolk when eggs are cold, but let the egg whites sit until they reach room temperature before you start to make the pavlova.

**I recommend peaking through the oven door to make sure your pavlova isn’t browning in the first 5-7 minutes. If you see it turning brown, simply turn the temperature down a 5-10 degrees.

.

.

get low, get low, get lo mein 🥡 • apparently this is the theme of the month but I’m addicted to lo mein of all varieties especially this better than take out veggie version.
____
VEGETABLE LO MEIN
20 minutes | Serves 4

Ingredients
1 lb lo mein noodle (Twin Marquis)
5 oz napa cabbage
2 oz red bell pepper, sliced
4 stalk green onion, chopped 1-inch
1 oz bean sprouts
2 oz carrot, julienned
2 clove garlic, minced

Stir-fry Sauce
1.5 tbsp light soy sauce
2 tbsp oyster sauce
1 tbsp dark soy sauce
White pepper
0.5 tsp cornstarch
1 tbsp sugar

Prepare vegetables.
Slice Napa cabbage into strips, making sure the stems are sliced thinner than the leaves as you work your way up from stem to leaf. 

Slice green onions into 1-inch pieces, separate the whites. Set aside. 

Prepare noodles. 
Cook noodles according to package instructions.  Set aside a cup of noodle water then drain and set aside. 

Prepare sauce by whisking together all the ingredients. 

Heat a wok on medium-high. While the wok heats up, add oil. As it begins to smoke add garlic and green onion whites. Then, add carrots, bell peppers and cabbage stems. Toss together for about 2-3 minutes. Then add cabbage leaves and bean sprouts and continue to cook for another minute.

Add noodles and combine before adding the green onion. Lastly add three tablespoons of the noddle water and stir fry sauce. Continue to toss for a minute. 

Serve topped with chili oil.

For the first time, I want to go somewhere where no one knows my name. I want to remember who I was before all these labels were plastered on me. MAPO TOFU WITH PACKET
1 box silken tofu
3 ounces ground pork
1 tbsp grated ginger
3 cloves garlic, minced
1 tsp cornstarch mixed with 2 tbsp water
1/2 cup water
Sichuan peppercorn, optional
3 scallions, chopped

Heat neutral oil in a medium saucepan, add garlic, ginger, whites of the scallion, and Sichuan peppercorn and dried chilies (optional). Cook for 1 minute, or until fragrant.  Add ground pork and cook for about 3-4 minutes, meat should be slightly browned. 

Add mapo tofu packet. Then add cornstarch slurry and water. Lastly, add tofu and bring to a simmer. Top with scallions and serve over a bed of rice.

STUFFED FRENCH TOAST
1 loaf of milk bread (or similar)
2 eggs
A pinch of salt
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
1 teaspoon cinnamon
1 teaspoon lime zest

For berry compote:
1 cup mixed berries
1 tbsp lim juice
1/4 cup eater
1/4 cup sugar 
Lime zest

Toppings:
Whipped cream
Maple syrup
Fresh fruit

METHOD
Prepare the berry compote. Add berries, sugar, lime juice, and water to a small sauce pan on medium-high heat. Once bubbling, reduce heat and muddle berries. The mixture should be thick in consistency. Transfer compote to a storage container and let cool in the fridge for at least an hour.

Cut two slices of the loaf - approximately 1 inch and 2 inches slices. Gently carve out the center of the 2 inch slice. Please note to leave enough so the filling doesn’t leak through.

In a shallow plate, whisk together eggs, salt, vanilla, cinnamon and lemon zest.

Once compote has cooled, place it into the hollow of the 2-inch slice. Cover the the slice with the 1inch slice. Dredge the toast in the egg mixture. 

Heat oil in a medium sauce. First fry the sides to seal the loaf, then fridge the top and bottom until golden brown. Drain on a paper towel if necessary.

Serve French toast topped with whipped cream, compote or fresh fruit, and a drizzle of maple syrup.

____

Lemon Yogurt Cake

64g yogurt 
100g sugar 
125g cake flour 
1 egg
1 tsp almond extract
Grated zest of two lemons
Pinch of salt
1 teaspoon baking powder
2 tbsp olive oil

1 tbsp lemon juice
130g powdered sugar
Lemon zest
1 tsp melted salted butter

Preheat oven to 350. Line the bottom of a 4-inch round springform pan with parchment paper, and set aside.

In a large bowl combine yogurt, almond extract and eggs. Slowly add in sugar until dissolved. Mix in flour, salt, baking powder. Lastly, add in lemon zest and olive oil. 

Pour in batter and bake for 40 minutes. Let cool. Top with icing. 

To make lemon icing, combine powdered sugar, lemon juice, melted butter and lemon zest.

There’s 10 minutes. Here’s a serving of egg noodles with plump oyster mushrooms topped with katsuobushi for an added umami flavor. 

UMAMI EGG NOODLES
2 tablespoons olive oil
100g oyster mushrooms
160g egg noodles

1/4 cup water
1 tbsp tamari
1 tbsp sugar
1 tbsp mirin

15g Shio kombu
2 tbsp salted butter
1 lemon cheek
1 sprig parsley, chopped
1 teaspoon black pepper, cracked
Katsuobushi

METHOD
Prepare tamari and mirin mixture by combining tamari, mirin and sugar. Bring to a simmer then remove from heat and set aside. 

Heat olive oil in a separate saucepan over a medium-high. Add oyster mushrooms and lightly fry until golden brown. Add shio kombu, and 2 tbsp of tamari and mirin mixture then combine. Remove from heat. 

Prepare a medium-sized pot with salted, boiling water. Cook pasta until al dente. Add cooked pasta, butter and a little pasta water to shio kombu. Add parsley, black pepper and a squeeze of lemon then toss to combine. Transfer the pasta to a serving plate and top with katsuobushi.

Not your Malaysian mom’s typical chili crab but a marriage of flavors that you’ll want to make for your next dinner party or date night in.  Chili crab is one of my favorite Malaysian/ Singaporean dishes - the combination of intense aromatics and sweet, creamy crab meat is just *chefs kiss*. Here’s my rendition of this iconic southeast Asian dish, combined with linguine. Enjoy! 🦀 

___
Chili Crab Linguine
Serves 4 | 40 minutes

INGREDIENTS
- 250g dried linguine pasta
- Whole crab, cleaned**
- 250g lump crab meat
- 5 holland red chili (or similar mild red chili pepper)
- 5 cloves garlic
- 1 large shallot
- 2 pieces Galanga root
- 2 tbsp grated ginger
- Candle nut or macadamia nut
- 1 tbsp soy bean paste, tacau
- 2 tbsp neutral oil
- 1/4 cup tomato sauce
- 1 cup water
- Salt and pepper to taste
- Coriander leaves, to garnish

** I used soft shell crab for this recipe that I then deep fried after it marinaded in the fried chili sauce but typically, you can use any kind of crab.
METHOD
1. Prepare aromatics - garlic, galanga, shallots, peppers. Place in a food processor and blend with candlenut or macadamia nut until it becomes a paste. 

2. Cook linguine pasta according to package instructions until al dente. Drain and set aside.

3. In a separate pan, heat oil over medium heat. Sauté soy bean paste and chili paste until fragrant. 

4. Add the  crabs to the pan and cook until the shells turn bright orange and the meat is cooked.

5. Reduce heat, then add tomato sauce and jumbo lump crab to sauce and bring to a simmer. 

6. Transfer the cooked linguine to the pan with the crab sauce. Toss the pasta to coat evenly with the sauce. Add 1/4 cup excess pasta water to the sauce. 

7. Serve hot with coriander leaves

When someone is in your life for a reason, it is usually to meet a need you have expressed. They have come to assist you through a difficulty; to provide you with guidance and support; to aid you physically, emotionally or spiritually. They may seem like a godsend, and they are. They are there for the reason you need them to be. Then, without any wrongdoing on your part or at an inconvenient time, this person will say or do something to bring the relationship to an end. Sometimes they pass. Sometimes they walk away. Sometimes they act up and force you to take a stand. What we must realize is that our need has been met, our desire fulfilled; their work is done. The prayer you sent up has been answered and now it is time to move on. 

Some people come into your life for a season, because your turn has come to share, grow or learn. They bring you an experience of peace or make you laugh. They may teach you something you have never done. They usually give you an unbelievable amount of joy. Believe it. It is real. But only for a season.

Lifetime relationships teach you lifetime lessons; things you must build upon in order to have a solid emotional foundation. Your job is to accept the lesson, love the person, and put what you have learned to use in all other relationships and areas of your life.

Your new life is going to cost you your old one. It’s going to cost you your comfort zone and your sense of direction. It’s going to cost you relationships and friends. It’s going to cost you being liked and understood. But it doesn’t matter.

This is a super simple go-to on the weeks when there’s not a moment to spare. I usually make a batch of these soy marinated eggs - inspired by traditional Mayak Gyeren - along with a few single serving portions rice on Sunday. So for a quick meal, I reheat the rice and top it with these gorgeous orange jammy soy marinated eggs.

____
INGREDIENTS 
6 large eggs - room temperature
1/2 cup soy sauce
1/2 cup water
1/4 cup mirin
2 closes garlic, minced
3 stalks scallions, chopped
1-2 Green hot peppers, chopped
2 tbsp Red chili flakes
1 tbsp Sesame seeds

METHOD
Bring a medium pot of water to a full rolling boil.  Add eggs and boil for 7 minutes.

Meanwhile, prepare a medium bowl with water and ice cubes.  When eggs are ready, remove eggs from water and place them directly into the ice bath. Set your timer for 3 minutes.

In the meantime, prepare marinate.  Combine soy sauce, water, mirin, garlic, scallions, hot peppers, chili flakes, and sesame seeds.

Peel the eggs and add them to the marinate.  Refrigerate for at least 3 hours.  Service over a bed of warm fluffy rice.

My cucumber obsession continues. I eat this salad a few times a week - it’s a combination of creamy avocado and crisp cucumbers tossed together in a refreshing dressing with a touch of red chili flakes (gochugaru) and topped with sesame seeds and scallions. The perfect summer side, meal or however you want to label it.

____
Cucumber and Avocado Salad
10 minutes | Serves 4

INGREDIENTS
3 Persian cucumbers, sliced 1 inch
1 avocado, cut into cubes
2 tbsp lemon juice
Salt and pepper, to taste 
1 tbsp Gochugaru (sub. chili flakes)
6 tbsp olive oil
1 tbsp scallions (sub. shallots)
1 tbsp sesame seeds (optional)

METHOD
In a medium bowl, combine cucumbers and avocado.  Add a pinch of salt and toss together until the avocado coats the cucumber.  Set aside. 

In a separate bowl, combine lemon juice, salt and pepper, gochugaru. Then vigorously whisk in olive oil until creamy.

Pour dressing over avocado and cucumbers. Toss together with scallions and sesame seeds. Serve and enjoy!

______
INGREDIENTS
Arctic char
Salad mix
Cooked quinoa
Cucumbers
Radish

FOR THE MARINADE (approx 2 pounds of Arctic char, vibes)
1/4 cup soy sauce
1 tbsp honey
1 tbsp grated ginger 
3 tbsp olive oil
1 tbsp yuzu or lemon juice
1 tbsp chopped scallions, optional

Whisk together all ingredients and marinade Arctic char for about 20 minutes. Remove protein from marinade. Heat a pan with olive and cook on medium heat for about 5-7 minutes or until slightly seared. Remove from heat and toss in sesame seeds. 

FOR THE DRESSING
2 tbsp Olive oil
1/2 shallot, minced
1 tbsp yuzu or lemon juice
1 tbsp rice vinegar
1/2 tbsp miso

Add yuzu, rice vinegar, miso and shallots to a bowl. Then vigorously whisk in olive oil until creamy. 

FOR ASSEMBLY
Create a bed of greens and grain at the bottom of a medium bowl. Top with Arctic char, cucumbers, radishes and drizzle with dressing.

I didn’t get to take my annual summer trip this year so I’m living my best life here in New York by making my favorite Italian dishes. Today, we are devouring Pasta al Limone (lemon pasta) - a fragrant and creamy-without-the-cream dish that is absolutely divine. I prepared this version with pecorino romano even though more classic recipes call for parmesan. I also used pici - a thick spaghetti - which I usually reserve for ragù or cacio e pepe, but it was all I had in the pantry. This dish is incredibly simple - it combines olive oil, lemon zest, lemon juice, lemon basil, starchy pasta water; tossed together to finish cooking the pasta and topped with cheese. 
______
Pasta al Limone
Serves 2

INGREDIENTS
Juice of 1 lemon
Zest of 1 lemon
1 tbsp olive oil
2-3 sprigs of basil (or lemon basil)
2 servings of spaghetti or linguine
Parmesan (or Pecorino Romano)

METHOD
Cook pasta according to package instructions, with 2-3 minutes to spare. 

While the pasta is cooking, prepare the sauce by heating oil in a saucepan on medium-high. Add half of the lemon zest and the leftover lemon rind. Cook for about 1 minute. Drop hear to medium-low, add lemon juice and season with a salt and pepper. Then, add one ladleful of pasta water and pasta. Finish cooking the pasta in the lemon sauce until al dente, about 2-3 minutes. Add cheese, and combine until creamy. *This is where you can taste an add additional salt or pepper if needed. 

Stir in remainder of lemon zest and lemon basil. Serve topped with freshly grated cheese.

KOREAN ZUCCHINI SALAD
1 zucchini
1 tbsp sesame oil
1 tsp sesame seeds
1 scallion, sliced
2 cloves garlic, minced
Salt

Thinly slice zucchini into a medium bowl. Season with about 1/4 tablespoon of salt and set aside to release excess moisture.

This week,  I took a dumpling tour through New York’s Chinatown with Camila from my team. Dumplings come in so many varieties but the two most important things are the dumpling skin-to-filling ratio and of course, flavor. 

Nestled inside Mott Street Eatery is SAMIWAGO. This dumpling stall serves them plump and juicy with a thin skin. The go-to order is the fried pork and chive dumplings, but the fried shrimp and pork are a must try.

Then, hop over to Columbus Park across the street and enjoy them there. The dumplings here have a thicker skin, and even though I wanted them to be slightly crispier with a bit more meat, they’re still packed with flavor. 

We finished off the tour at SUPER TASTE. The dumplings here come extra crispy.  The dumplings here are packed with flavor and even though usually prefer my fried dumplings with just the bottoms crispy, this spot is definitely worth the try. We ended up pretty full, so we’re going to have to come back for the steamed ones next.

CAVATELLI IN A GUANCIALE, RED ONION AND TOMATO SAUCE
Serves 4 | Time: 30 minutes

INGREDIENTS 
4 oz guanciale, cut into ¼-inch cubes
1 medium red onion, diced 
1 teaspoon red pepper flakes
4 cups canned whole, peeled tomatoes with purée
4 servings of cavatelli
Extra virgin olive oil
Freshly grated parmigiano-reggiano 

METHOD
In a medium saucepan, cook the guanciale over medium heat until slightly crisp, about 5 minutes. Add onions and cook until tender not browned, about 3 minutes. Lower heat to medium-low if onions begin to brown. 

Add the red pepper flakes and tomatoes, turn the heat to medium-low, and simmer for about 5 to 8 minutes. Season with salt and pepper.

Add cooked cavatelli to the sauce along with 2 tbsp of pasta water. Simmer for 1 minute to let the cavatelli absorb the sauce. Drizzle with olive oil, and serve with grated Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese.

Romanticizing soup season with a combination of flavors that feel like a warm hug. I make this version of coconut curry soup (Tom Kha Koong) a few times a month when the temperature drops and it’s always a crowd pleaser when I’m hosting. 
_____

INGREDIENTS
1/2 pound of shrimp, deveined and shells removed
1 stalk of lemongrass ends
2 cloves of garlic, minced
1/2 white onion, diced
1-2 Thai red chilies or similar, chopped for extra spicy
1 tsp of grated galanga or ginger
1 tomatoes, quartered
2 tbsp red curry paste
1/2 can coconut cream
3-4 curry leaves
1 tbsp sugar
2 cups stock of choice
1 tbsp sauce
1 lime
 

In a 5 oz pot, sautée onions, garlic, lemongrass and chilies with coconut oil on medium-low heat for about 2 minutes. Add protein, grate in galanga (or ginger) and cook for about 3-4 minutes,. Then, add curry paste and cook for 2 minutes. Finally, add stock and coconut cream, tomatoes curry leaves, coconut sugar. Drop heat to low and let the broth reduce, about 15 minutes. 

Turn off heat and add vegetables of choice and place lid over the pot to let the vegetables cook down and the protein to absorb more flavor. Remove lemongrass stalks and curry leaves from broth. 

Finish with fish sauce and lime juice. Add cilantro, optional. Serve with rice or on its own.

Oh and as for black pepper chicken? Classic takeout dish at home that’s easier than you think - make it under 30 and top it off with a side of rive.  Here’s the solo recipe, even though this chicken breast was big enough for two. 

________

BLACK PEPPER CHICKEN
1 chicken breast, sliced 1 inch
1/2 bell pepper, chopped
1/2 onion, chopped
1-2 tbsp peppercorn, crushed
Red Thai chilis, optional
1 tbsp soy sauce
1 tbsp oyster sauce
1 tbsp sweet soy sauce
1 tbsp Cornstarch 
Shaoxing wine

Sauce
1 tbsp sweet soy sauce
1 tbsp oyster sauce 
1 tbsp water
1/2 tbsp cornstarch

METHOD
Combine soy sauce, oyster sauce, sweet soy sauce and cornstarch in a medium bowl. Add sliced chicken and coat evenly. Cover and let marinade for 30 minutes. 

In a large wok or skillet, heat neutral oil on medium-high. Add chicken and cook for about 7 minutes. Add bell peppers and onions and cook for another 2-3 minutes. Deglaze pan with shaoxing wine. Cook for another 2-3 minutes. Add in black pepper, then, add sauce and combine. 

Serve with rice.

Had to share my own version of butter beans for the cold days ahead. This creamy, heartwarming dish packs a punch of zest and spice with every bite and is best served with a fresh baguette. 

_______
Creamy Butter Beans

INGREDIENTS
1 can (15 oz) butter beans
1 small onion (~1/4 cup), diced
1 cup leeks
1 head of garlic
1 tbsp lemon zest
1/2 can coconut milk
salt and pepper, to taste
1/2 - 1 tbsp chili oil
Parsley

METHOD
Preheat oven to 400ºF.  Slice the head of garlic in half and place onto a large piece of foil. Drizzle the garlic with olive oil and seal tin foil. Roast in oven for about 30 minutes. 

Heat oil in a saucepan on medium-high. Add onions and leeks, and sauté for about 2-3 minutes. Season with salt and pepper. Add beans and roasted garlic, and cook for another 2-3 minutes. Drop heat to low and add coconut cream, lemon zest and let simmer for about 7-10 minutes. Finish with chili oil.

 Top butter beans with fresh herbs like parsley, and serve with a fresh baguette.

If you’re a last-minute girlie like me but love to host, here’s my one tip: simplify everything and make recipes that allow you to multi-task. These mini baked potatoes are inspired by the famous baked potato at Caviar Kaspia. These miniature versions are very simple to make and a perfect last-minute appetizer to add to the menu. 

____
MINI BAKED POTATOES WITH CAVIAR

INGREDIENTS
1 pound small creamer potatoes
2 tablespoon chives, finely chopped
100g Caviar
8 oz Crème fraîche

METHOD
Preheat oven to 425°F. Place potatoes on a baking sheet. Cover with tin foil and bake for 45 minutes, remove tin foil and bake for another 10 minutes.

Remove from oven and let cool for 5 minutes. Cut an opening in the center of each potato and push the sides of each potato to loosen the flesh of the potatoes. Add crème fraîche and allow it to melt into the center.

Before serving, add a dollop of caviar and a sprinkle of chives onto each potato.

My favorite form of self-care - ending each day dancing in the kitchen while making a nice meal. Let’s make - spicy wontons. Trust me, they’re easier than you think.

INGREDIENTS

WONTON FILLING
1/2 pound ground protein of choice - pork or chicken
1 tbsp corn starch 1/2 tsp Salt
1 tsp Sesame oil
1 tsp chicken bouillon 
1/2 oyster sauce
1/2 tsp white Pepper
1 egg
3 tbsp aromatic water

AROMATIC WATER
1 tbsp grated ginger
1 tbsp scallion
3 tbsp boiling hot water
1/4 tsp salt

CHILI OIL SAUCE
5 tbsp Chinese chili flakes
2 tbsp sesame seeds
1 cup neutral oil (grapeseed)
1 tsp Chinese five spice powder
1 teaspoon ground sichuan peppercorn
1/2 tbsp Sweet soy sauce
1/2 tbsp light brown sugar
Cilantro

METHOD
Prepare aromatic water by combining ginger, scallion, salt. Pour 1/4 cup of boiling water over the mixture and let it steep, set aside to cool.

Prepare homemade chili oil by combining homemade chili chili flakes, sesame seeds, Chinese five spice, Sichuan peppercorn.  Add oil and bring to a simmer. Remove from heat and set aside.

To make the wonton filling, combine protein, corn starch, salt, chicken bouillon, oyster sauce, white pepper, egg, and 3 tbsp of aromatic water. Combine using a fork or chopsticks till all ingredients are combined.

Fold filling into wonton mixture, boil for 5-7 minutes. 

In a medium bowl, make chili oil sauce by combine homemade chili oil with sweet soy sauce, cilantro. Then add wontons and drizzle with more chili oil and fresh cilantros.

On a somber, rain-soaked day, there is a peculiar solace to be found in a humble bowl of beef stew. This timeless classic always brings comfort to the soul,  a sanctuary of nourishment for both body and spirit. Each bite a love letter that feels like a warm hug. 

Growing up, my mom would prepare this for us, and when I moved to New York and began enduring the long winters, it was one of the first things I learned to cook. The combination of succulent cubes of beef, seared to a rich, caramelized perfection, married with robust root vegetables, aromatic herbs and earthy spices is a slow-cooked masterpiece to be savored.
_____
Hearty Beef Stew

INGREDIENTS
1 - 1.5 pound of chuck or top sirloin, cubed into 1-inch pieces
1 tbsp  garlic powder
1 tbsp onion powder
1 tsp salt
1 tsp pepper
2 tablespoons cornstarch (for dredging)
2 tablespoons olive oil
1 large onion, chopped
3 cloves garlic, minced
4 cups beef broth
1 cup red wine
2 bay leaves
2 sprigs of thyme
2 sprigs of rosemary
4 carrots, sliced 
4 potatoes, diced
2 tbsp flour for thickening
1 tbsp tomato paste
Salt and pepper, to taste

Combine garlic powder, onion powder, salt and pepper to a bowl.  Add beef, and make sure to evenly coat.  Then, add cornstarch.

Heat the  oil in a large Dutch oven or heavy-bottomed pot over medium-high heat. Add the cubed beef to the pot and brown it on all sides, working in batches. Remove the browned beef and set it aside.

In the same pot, add the chopped onion and sauté for about 3-4 minutes until translucent. Add the minced garlic and cook for an additional minute. Add tomato paste, then sprinkle in flour and stir well to combine. 

Return the browned beef to the pot, and pour in red wine to deglaze the pan. Stir in the beef broth, bay leaves, thyme, and rosemary and root vegetables. Bring the mixture to a boil, cover, then reduce the heat to low and let it simmer for about 1.5 to 2 hours, or until the beef is tender.

Season the stew with salt and pepper to taste. Remove rosemary stems and bay leaves.

Serve the beef stew garnished with chopped fresh herbs if desired.
